%20beyond%20a%20job%20seeker's%20responses%20in%20an%20interview.%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3EStacie%20Haller%20of%20ResumeBuilder.com%20finds%20showing%20up%20too%20early%20could%20be%20a%20problem%2C%20for%20instance.%3C%2Fli%3E%3C%2Ful%3E%3Cp%3EGetting%20to%20the%20office%20way%20too%20early%2C%20not%20having%20a%20professional%20background%20for%20virtual%20interviews%2C%20and%20not%20knowing%20your%20prospective%20employer's%20mission%20could%20all%20be%20potential%20red%20flags%20you're%20giving%20in%20a%20job%20interview.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EStacie%20Haller%2C%20the%20chief%20career%20advisor%20with%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.resumebuilder.com%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EResumeBuilder.com%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20pointed%20out%20to%20Business%20Insider%20problems%20that%20go%20beyond%20how%20an%20interviewee%20actually%20responds%20to%20questions%2C%20like%3Cstrong%3E%20%3C%2Fstrong%3Enot%20looking%20at%20the%20interviewer%20or%20not%20bringing%20up%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fquestions-to-ask-in-job-interview-to-get-the-role-2024-5%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Egood%20questions%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EShe%20suggests%20keeping%20in%20mind%20that%20a%20prospective%20employer%20is%20interested%20in%20how%20you%20can%20help%20them%2C%20and%20you%20want%20to%20show%20that%20throughout%20the%20process%20%E2%80%94%20including%20after%20the%20interview%20with%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fshould-you-write-thank-you-note-email-after-interview-2022-10%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ethank-you%20note%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThe%20most%20important%20is%20to%20understand%20they're%20going%20to%20hire%20the%20person%20that%20is%20prepared%2C%20is%20interested%2C%20can%20articulate%20why%20they're%20the%20best%20person%20for%20the%20job%2C%26quot%3B%20Haller%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBelow%20are%20some%20things%20you%20might%20be%20doing%20wrong%20at%20the%20interview%20stage.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22af4fc9d6-2191-4641-9029-b22a3f9233a8%5C%22%3ENot%20focusing%20on%20the%20interviewer%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EA%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.glassdoor.com%2Fblog%2Fguide%2Fwhat-not-to-do-in-an-interview%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EGlassdoor%20blog%20post%3C%2Fa%3E%20said%20people%20shouldn't%20be%20looking%20at%20their%20phones.%20%26quot%3BAnswering%20calls%2C%20texting%2C%20or%20even%20looking%20to%20see%20who%20is%20calling%20during%20an%20interview%20is%20unprofessional%20and%20shows%20your%20interviewer%20that%20you%20are%20not%20paying%20attention%2C%26quot%3B%20the%20post%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EInstead%2C%20people%20should%20be%20looking%20at%20the%20person%20interviewing%20them.%20Haller%20said%20interviewees%20should%20practice%20making%20eye%20contact%2C%20particularly%20if%20they're%20doing%20a%20virtual%20interview%20and%20not%20used%20to%20talking%20this%20way.%20%26quot%3BIf%20I'm%20on%20a%20video%20with%20someone%20interviewing%20and%20they're%20not%20looking%20at%20me%2C%20that's%20a%20turnoff%2C%26quot%3B%20she%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAn%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.indeed.com%2Fcareer-advice%2Finterviewing%2Fwhat-not-to-do-in-an-interview%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EIndeed%20post%3C%2Fa%3E%20from%20career%20coach%20Jamie%20Birt%20also%20pointed%20out%20avoiding%20eye%20contact%20or%20even%20looking%20down%20as%20things%20to%20watch%20out%20for%20because%20interviewers%20%26quot%3Bcould%20misinterpret%20this%20as%20a%20sign%20of%20weakness%20or%20lying.%26quot%3B%20Birt%20suggested%20pretending%20the%20interview%20is%20a%20conversation%20with%20a%20friend.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22ac1a95fc-d7b0-4fe8-883e-1292aad21bb5%5C%22%3ENot%20getting%20to%20the%20interview%20at%20a%20reasonable%20time%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EHaller%20said%20it's%20not%20good%20to%20be%20at%20an%20interview%20too%20early.%20%26quot%3BBecause%20then%20they're%20going%20to%20interpret%20it%20that%20you%20have%20no%20sense%20of%20timing%20and%20what's%20appropriate%2C%26quot%3B%20she%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThat%20doesn't%20mean%20you%20want%20to%20wait%20until%20the%20last%20minute%20to%20get%20to%20the%20interview.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BI%20recommend%20if%20it's%20in%20person%2C%20you%20could%20get%20there%20and%20leave%20plenty%20of%20early%20time%2C%26quot%3B%20Haller%20said.%20%26quot%3BJust%20don't%20go%20up%20to%20the%20office%20yet.%20Get%20yourself%20prepared.%20Go%20upstairs%20or%20inside%20or%20wherever%20the%20interview%20is%20about%20five%20minutes%20before%20your%20interview.%20Five%20to%2010%20minutes%20is%20absolutely%20fine.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EShe%20said%20job%20candidates%20shouldn't%20be%20late%20to%20virtual%20calls%20either%2C%20so%20practice%20using%20the%20technology%20for%20the%20virtual%20chat%20before%20the%20interview%20to%20avoid%20technical%20difficulties.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BWhat%20you%20do%20during%20an%20interview%20tells%20that%20person%20what%20you're%20going%20to%20be%20like%20to%20work%20with%2C%26quot%3B%20Haller%20said.%20%26quot%3BSo%20if%20you're%20late%20for%20an%20interview%2C%20they%20already%20think%20you're%20going%20to%20be%20late%20to%20work.%20Why%20would%20I%20hire%20you%3F%20Unless%20you%20have%20an%20appropriate%20excuse%2C%20and%20you%20make%20that%20appropriate%20phone%20call%2C%20things%20happen.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%225648eb53-2dc5-4d41-bc0f-f7ced8ae49bc%5C%22%3ENot%20being%20polite%20to%20people%20beyond%20the%20interviewer%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EHaller%20finds%20the%20conversation%20the%20job%20candidate%20has%20with%20the%20person%20working%20at%20the%20front%20desk%20is%20actually%20part%20of%20the%20interview.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BAs%20a%20hiring%20manager%20for%20many%20years%2C%20and%20I%20hired%20all%20office%20personnel%20and%20salespeople%2C%20I%20would%20always%20go%20back%20to%20the%20receptionist%20and%20say%2C%20'How%20was%20it%20when%20this%20person%20came%20in%3F'%20And%20if%20that%20person%20was%20not%20nice%20or%20rude%20to%20my%20receptionist%2C%20that%20was%20just%20as%20much%20part%20of%20the%20interview%20as%20what%20they%20said%20to%20me%2C%26quot%3B%20she%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBirt's%20Indeed%20post%20similarly%20noted%20not%20to%20be%20rude.%20%26quot%3BThe%20interviewer%20will%20likely%20ask%20the%20employees%20you%20met%20during%20your%20time%20at%20the%20company%20for%20their%20impression%20of%20you%2C%26quot%3B%20the%20Indeed%20post%20said.%20%26quot%3BInstead%20of%20being%20standoffish%2C%20greet%20everyone%20you%20encounter%20during%20your%20interview%20with%20kindness%20and%20a%20smile.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22a0358fbf-858e-45c8-b2ec-91d6ee874a37%5C%22%3EYour%20responses%20to%20commonly%20asked%20interview%20questions%20aren't%20great%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EOne%20common%20question%20is%20about%20a%20job%20candidate's%20weaknesses.%20Haller%20said%20she%20doesn't%20think%20%26quot%3Bpeople%20are%20really%20asking%20for%20your%20weakness.%20What%20they're%20asking%20for%20is%20are%20you%20self-aware%20and%20do%20you%20know%20what%20you%20need%20to%20work%20on%20and%20compensate%3F%20That's%20what%20they%20really%20want%20to%20know.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EFor%20answering%20questions%20about%20why%20you%20want%20the%20job%2C%20Haller%20said%2C%20%26quot%3BPeople%20don't%20care%20what%20you%20want.%26quot%3B%20It's%20more%20about%20your%20knowledge%20of%20the%20company.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThey%20want%20to%20know%20you're%20interested%20in%20working%20for%20them%2C%20but%20they%20don't%20care%20if%20it's%20a%20great%20first%20job%20for%20you%20or%20any%20other%20reasons%20that%20really%20don't%20matter%20to%20why%20they%20would%20hire%20you%2C%26quot%3B%20Haller%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHaller%20said%20for%20that%20question%20job%20seekers%20should%20demonstrate%20that%20they%20took%20the%20time%20to%20research%20the%20employer%2C%20including%20what%20has%20been%20said%20in%20the%20news.%20Haller%20finds%20people%20can%20also%20express%20their%20interest%20in%20being%20part%20of%20the%20employer's%20mission%20and%20team.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BEvery%20answer%20in%20an%20interview%20has%20to%20be%20about%20why%20you're%20the%20best%20person%20for%20the%20job%2C%20period%2C%26quot%3B%20Haller%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWinging%20your%20understanding%20of%20the%20company%20during%20the%20interview%20could%20also%20be%20problematic.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIf%20I'm%20interviewing%20someone%20and%20they%20don't%20even%20know%20what%20my%20company%20does%2C%20or%20what%20our%20mission%20is%2C%20or%20anything%20about%20us%2C%20that%20is%20a%20huge%20red%20flag%2C%26quot%3B%20Haller%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%2289d5295d-a40a-4085-802f-cd2db82bc5c6%5C%22%3ENot%20preparing%20answers%20about%20skills%20or%20other%20things%20the%20employer%20is%20looking%20for%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EAmid%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fhow-to-get-job-without-college-degree-amazon-intel-ibm-2024-3%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Epopularity%20of%20skills-based%20hiring%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20you%20might%20want%20to%20show%20off%20your%20skills%20during%20the%20interview%2C%20even%20if%20not%20directly%20asked%20about%20them.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20team%20collaboration%20is%20important%20in%20the%20job%20posting%2C%20Haller%20said%20to%20include%20that%20in%20a%20story%20you%20tell%20during%20the%20interview.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBirt's%20Indeed%20post%20said%20to%20avoid%20lying%20about%20skills%20and%20other%20things%20during%20the%20interview%2C%20though%2C%20and%20not%20to%20be%20arrogant.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BDisplaying%20pride%20can%20make%20interviewers%20feel%20as%20if%20you%20are%20talking%20down%20to%20them%2C%26quot%3B%20Birt%20said.%20%26quot%3BInstead%2C%20discuss%20your%20skills%20and%20accomplishments%20in%20connection%20with%20how%20they%20can%20help%20the%20company%20and%20in%20a%20straightforward%2C%20not%2